VA officials talk about implementing changes & making improvements, but it's past time to execute these ideas & make this right for our veterans.

In Central AL, there have been times a veteran has sought out mental health care, received no follow-up, & it resulted in suicide. We have a real problem in some of our VA health care systems. We have failed our veterans time & time again. Now, 20 of them are giving up each day.

20 veterans commit suicide every day. This is a tragedy we must treat as more than just a number. Only 6 of the 20 who are taking their own lives received VA care in the 2 years prior to their death. One reason that's the case: Veterans don't trust the VA to take care of them. pic.twitter.com/yKXwBSNcw5

In Central AL, not only do we lack the personnel to handle caring for veterans at the VA, we also have a hard time recruiting outside providers because the VA makes it difficult to exchange medical records. According to the VA’s own data, the Central AL VA continues to be a terrible VA health care system. I am sick & tired of getting status quo answers as to why. This is a huge disservice to our veterans, & I will not stop making the case to Secretary Wilkie until we get this right.

ICYMI: This week, I spoke to VA Secretary Robert Wilkie during a MilCon-VA Appropriations Subcommittee hearing. I explained to him the severity of the problems our veterans face in Southeast Alabama. https://riponadvance.com/stories/veterans-healthcare-just-isnt-working-roby-tells-va-secretary/ …
